\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 ECIO Cybersecurity Incident Response Program
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Program Establishment
\series default
.
 The ECIO shall maintain a formal cybersecurity incident response program to detect,
 contain,
 eradicate,
 and recover from cybersecurity incidents affecting IT systems,
 services,
 and infrastructure under the Department's management.
 The program is established and governed by this policy.
 It is a subordinate program framework within the ECIO Policy Manual and operates within the governance structure established across Chapters 1 through 3 and Chapter 5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The ECIO does not maintain a formally designated,
 standing Incident Response Team.
 Cybersecurity incident response is executed by IT Department personnel under Incident Commander authority.
 The absence of a standing team does not diminish the rigor or authority of the program;
 it reflects the Department's operating model,
 in which response authority is vested in defined roles rather than a standing team construct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Commander
\series default
.
 The IT Director shall serve as Incident Commander for all cybersecurity incidents by default.
 The IT Director may designate any IT Department staff member as Incident Commander for a specific incident;
 designations shall be made at the time they become effective and documented in the incident record.
 The Incident Commander shall exercise final authority over all incident response activity for the duration of the incident.
 This title is singular within the ECIO framework —
 no parallel title exists.
 The Incident Commander role is established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 Section 6.3 and incorporated into Chapter 4 by reference without modification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Declaration Authority
\series default
.
 Authority to declare a cybersecurity incident shall reside with the IT Director and the Assistant IT Director.
 A designated Tier L3+ technical lead may declare a cybersecurity incident only when the IT Director and the Assistant IT Director are both genuinely unavailable and the operational situation requires immediate action.
 The technical lead(s) authorized to exercise this authority shall be identified in writing by the IT Director in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and reviewed at least annually.
 Upon declaration,
 all operational authority shall transfer immediately and exclusively to the Incident Commander.
 Administrative stand-ins shall not intervene in,
 delay,
 or countermand Incident Commander directives.
 Fiscal Affairs and Purchasing shall process Incident Commander emergency procurement requests without delay.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Severity Classification
\series default
.
 Chapter 4 shall use a three-tier severity classification to categorize cybersecurity incidents.
 This classification is independent of,
 and does not interact with,
 the five-tier operational severity framework (Critical,
 Urgent,
 High,
 Normal,
 Low) established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 for service level management.
 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 SLA obligations are suspended for the duration of any active Chapter 4 incident per the Hard Fork mechanics established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 Section 6.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The three tiers are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
High
\series default
 —
 Incidents with confirmed or severe impact on operations,
 Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 or public safety systems.
 Examples include compromise of sensitive or CJI data,
 widespread malware or ransomware,
 unauthorized access to critical systems,
 and denial-of-service attacks affecting enterprise operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Medium
\series default
 —
 Incidents with significant current impact or confirmed potential for severe impact.
 Examples include small-scale denial-of-service attacks,
 website compromise,
 unauthorized access attempts with confirmed breach,
 and phishing campaigns with confirmed credential capture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Low
\series default
 —
 Incidents with minimal current impact but potential for escalation if unaddressed.
 Examples include network probes or reconnaissance scans,
 isolated virus infections,
 acceptable use violations,
 and unconfirmed anomalies under active investigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Severity may be reclassified upward or downward at any point during the response at the Incident Commander's direction.
 The initial severity classification shall be documented in the incident record at the time of declaration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
IR Lifecycle Framework
\series default
.
 The ECIO IR program shall be organized around a six-phase lifecycle:
 Preparation,
 Identification,
 Containment,
 Eradication,
 Recovery,
 and Lessons Learned.
 This is ECIO's selected framework,
 consistent with the incident response lifecycle model recognized in NIST SP 800-61 Rev.
 3,
 which affirms that organizations should use the lifecycle framework that best suits their operating model.
 Each phase is governed by one or more of the operational policies in Chapter 4,
 as mapped in Section 6.2 of this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Relationship to Operational Incident Management —
 Hard Fork
\series default
.
 The ECIO distinguishes between two categories of adverse IT events.
 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 governs operational incidents —
 unplanned technical failures whose resolution requires restoring service as quickly as possible.
 Chapter 4 governs cybersecurity incidents —
 events involving malicious activity,
 unauthorized access,
 data compromise,
 or any Indicator of Compromise as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 These two regimes are not interchangeable and one shall not be substituted for the other.
 A Chapter 4 response may deliberately extend an outage to stop active compromise,
 preserve forensic evidence,
 or prevent further damage;
 speed of restoration is subordinate to containment and forensic integrity.
\end_layout

